50|$|On June 16, 2007, the Topple Tower {{installation}} (known as Timber Tower) at Dollywood in Pigeon Forge, Tennessee, United States became stuck after {{a faulty}} <b>safety</b> <b>sensor</b> engaged. The tower {{was in an}} upright position with the gondola at the top. The safety system would not let operators override the sensor, leaving 40 passengers stranded on the ride, some {{for as many as}} 6 hours. As of the 2012 season, Dollywood has removed Timber Tower from the park, with the lawsuit between Huss and Dollywood resolved behind closed doors.|$|E
50|$|While {{on a tour}} of Mori Tower on {{the morning}} of March 26, 2004, six-year-old Ryo Mizokawa was killed in a {{revolving}} door at the building's second-floor main entrance. Mizokawa's head was crushed between the door rotating from his left and the outer frame; he died two hours after reaching the hospital. The door's motion <b>safety</b> <b>sensor</b> was originally set to detect anything standing 80 cm tall. This setting was changed to 135 cm, however, after the door began stopping unnecessarily when detecting a newly installed, nearby safety barrier. After the incident, it was revealed that 32 people had previously sustained injuries caused by revolving doors at Roppongi Hills since the complex opened less than a year earlier. In an out-of-court settlement, the Mizokawa family received an undisclosed compensation payment from the building's operator, Mori Building Company.|$|E
